	   <tr><td colspan=2>About Torrent of Pain, there actually seems to be a good thought behind it. First off, it's virtually no aggro at all. You can throw it on an incoming mob that someone just tagged with an arrow and you still wont get any attention from the mob. <br><br>Secondly, it's a great buff (47+ to attack) and melees always save a buff slot for it and actually ask you to cast it if you happen to miss once(unlike Torrent of Pain which adds 12ac, that slot could be used for something much more beneficial).<br><br>Thirdly, the resistance check isn't made on mr. Giant Captain in WW is for instance 100% mr but Torrent of Hate lands on him.<br><br>And fourth and last, it seems to have a zonewide range. If you are out pulling half way across an outdoors zone or deep in some dungeon the buff will still reach your party.<br><br>So, a shadowknight spell with no aggro, a meaningful purpose, that you can land even on fully magic resistant mobs and be nowhere near your party and still have them receive the benefits of. Seems the thought is to increase the usefulness of the shadowknight as a member of high level raids in my opinion and I think it works, to a degree at least. Shadowknights need a skilled player to come to their full potential :)<br><br>Torrent of Fatigue is perhaps also a part of this thought but as of yet it is unbelievably bugged (it seems to add 20 sta to the actual stat Stamina but for some reason it drains your sta bar. Even sitting, non-active characters will get their sta bar drained in roughly 30 seconds).<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Tue May 14 10:31:27 2002</em><br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
